Update ChangeLog

edac-ctl: add an option to display the memory layout

This helps to display how the memories are set inside the DIMM
sockets, by displaying the memory configuration on a graphics
art-text, like:

       +-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
       |                      mc0                      |                      mc1                      |
       | channel0  | channel1  | channel2  | channel3  | channel0  | channel1  | channel2  | channel3  |
-------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
slot3: |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |
slot2: |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |     0 MB  |
-------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+
slot1: |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |
slot0: |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |  4096 MB  |
-------+-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------+

That requires the HERM patches for this option to work. If not available,
it will display:
	edac-ctl: Error: No dimm layout information. Old kernel?

edac-ctl.in: Use system information DMI Type as fallback for mainboard detection

Some HP boards based on i7300 chipsets don't define BIOS DMI type 2
(board information), but they provide type 1 (system information).

Previous versions of EDAC were using either type, but, due to the way
the logic were written, the mainboard would always use the last information
at the dmidecode parser.

This patch re-adds DMI type 1 parsing, but with a somewhat different logic: now,
if both types are available, it will opt to use the board information.
